205	                "AlertEvent", savedEvent.getId().toString(),
206	                null, suppressed ? "SUPPRESSED" : "ACTIVE", alertType, null);
207	
208	        return new AlertEventResult(savedEvent, workOrder, durationEval);
209	    }
210	
211	    /**
212	     * Evaluates whether the threshold-exceeding condition has been sustained (unbroken)
213	     * for at least {@code durationSeconds}.
214	     *
215	     * <h3>Sustained-threshold duration model</h3>
216	     * <p>This implements the prompt's "configurable threshold duration window" as a
217	     * <strong>sustained-exceedance streak</strong>: the threshold must have been continuously
218	     * exceeded — with no intervening normal reading — for at least {@code durationSeconds}
219	     * before a work order is auto-created. This models real-world sensor scenarios like
220	     * "temperature &gt; 120°F for 5 continuous minutes before dispatching."</p>
221	     *
222	     * <h3>Algorithm (streak-walk)</h3>
223	     * <ol>
224	     *   <li>Query all events for this alert type + scope within a lookback window of
225	     *       {@code max(2 * durationSeconds, 3600)} seconds, ordered oldest-first.</li>
226	     *   <li>Walk chronologically. For each event:
227	     *       <ul>
228	     *         <li>If {@code thresholdExceeded(event.measuredValue)}: start a new streak
229	     *             (if none active) or continue the current one.</li>
230	     *         <li>If NOT exceeded: <strong>reset</strong> the streak — the condition cleared.</li>
231	     *       </ul></li>
232	     *   <li>After the walk, compute {@code streakSeconds = Duration(streakStart, now)}.</li>
233	     *   <li>Return {@code satisfied = (streakSeconds >= durationSeconds)}.</li>
234	     * </ol>
235	     *
236	     * <h3>Return value</h3>
237	     * <p>Returns a {@link DurationEvaluation} so callers and API responses can trace the
238	     * exact evaluation: streak start time, elapsed seconds, required seconds, and verdict.</p>
239	     */
240	    DurationEvaluation evaluateSustainedDuration(String alertType, String scopeType, String scopeId,
241	                                                  int durationSeconds, double threshold, String operator) {
242	        // Look back 2x duration (min 1 hour) to capture streak start with margin
243	        long lookbackSecs = Math.max((long) durationSeconds * 2, 3600);
244	        LocalDateTime lookback = LocalDateTime.now().minusSeconds(lookbackSecs);
245	        List<AlertEvent> recentEvents = alertEventRepository
246	                .findByAlertTypeAndScopeTypeAndScopeIdAndCreatedAtAfterOrderByCreatedAtAsc(
247	                        alertType, scopeType, scopeId, lookback);
248	
249	        if (recentEvents.isEmpty()) {
250	            // No prior events — first occurrence, streak has zero history
251	            return new DurationEvaluation(false, null, 0, durationSeconds);
252	        }
253	
254	        // Walk events chronologically to find the start of the current unbroken streak
255	        LocalDateTime streakStart = null;
256	        for (AlertEvent e : recentEvents) {
257	            if (thresholdExceeded(e.getMeasuredValue(), threshold, operator)) {
258	                // Threshold exceeded — begin or continue streak
259	                if (streakStart == null) {
260	                    streakStart = e.getCreatedAt();
261	                }
262	                // (if streakStart is already set, streak continues — no change)
263	            } else {
264	                // Threshold NOT exceeded — condition cleared, streak resets
265	                streakStart = null;
266	            }
267	        }
268	
269	        if (streakStart == null) {
270	            // Most recent event was below threshold — no active streak
271	            return new DurationEvaluation(false, null, 0, durationSeconds);
272	        }
273	
274	        long streakSeconds = java.time.Duration.between(streakStart, LocalDateTime.now()).getSeconds();
275	        boolean satisfied = streakSeconds >= durationSeconds;
276	        return new DurationEvaluation(satisfied, streakStart, streakSeconds, durationSeconds);
277	    }
278	
279	    private boolean thresholdExceeded(double measured, double threshold, String operator) {
280	        return switch (operator) {
281	            case "GT" -> measured > threshold;
282	            case "GTE" -> measured >= threshold;
283	            case "LT" -> measured < threshold;
284	            case "LTE" -> measured <= threshold;
285	            case "EQ" -> measured == threshold;
286	            default -> measured > threshold;
287	        };
288	    }
289	
290	    /**
291	     * Result of duration-window evaluation. Exposes the evaluation inputs and outputs
292	     * so callers (and API responses) can trace exactly why the duration check passed or failed.
293	     *
294	     * @param satisfied      true if the sustained-exceedance streak meets the required duration
295	     * @param streakStartedAt  timestamp of the first event in the current unbroken streak, or null
296	     * @param streakSeconds  elapsed seconds from streak start to evaluation time, or 0
297	     * @param requiredSeconds the configured durationSeconds for this rule
298	     */
299	    public record DurationEvaluation(boolean satisfied, LocalDateTime streakStartedAt,
300	                                      long streakSeconds, int requiredSeconds) {
301	        /** Duration is trivially satisfied when the rule requires 0 seconds. */
302	        static DurationEvaluation immediate() {
303	            return new DurationEvaluation(true, null, 0, 0);
304	        }
305	    }
306	
307	    public record AlertEventResult(AlertEvent alertEvent, WorkOrder workOrder,
308	                                    DurationEvaluation durationEvaluation) {}
309	}
